context: The first Europeans to disembark and explore the region were the <a1_0><b7_0>Portuguese<b7_0/><a1_0/> navigators Diogo Cão in <a2_0><b5_0>1485<b5_0/><a2_0/> and Bartolomeu Dias in <a0_0><b6_0>1486<b6_0/><a0_0/>; still the region was not claimed by the Portuguese crown. However, like most of Sub-Saharan Africa, Namibia was not extensively explored by Europeans until the 19th century, when traders and settlers arrived, principally from <a3_0><b9_0>Germany<b9_0/><a3_0/> and <b8_0>Sweden<b8_0/>. In the late 19th century Dorsland trekkers crossed the area on their way from the Transvaal to <a4_0>Angola<a4_0/>. Some of them settled in Namibia instead of continuing their journey.
